- Competition mode: __COMPETITION_MODE__
- Score acquisition path: __SCORE_ACQUISITION_PATH__
- Internet policy: __INTERNET_POLICY__
- Resource flags: __RESOURCE_FLAGS__
- Notebook runtime limit: __NOTEBOOK_RUNTIME_LIMIT__

## Metrics
- Primary: `public_rank` (position, lower is better)
- Secondary: `public_score` (__PUBLIC_SCORE_DIRECTION__ is better), `cv_score` (`__CV_METRIC_NAME__`, __CV_DIRECTION__ is better), `submission_count` (count)

## Keep / Discard Policy
- Keep when `public_rank` improves.
- If `public_rank` is unchanged, keep only when `public_score` improves.
- Otherwise discard.
- Use `--local-only` to decide whether a candidate is worth a real submission, but do not invent leaderboard gains from local CV alone.
- When the daily submission cap is exhausted, switch to provisional local mode:
  - keep candidates that materially improve `cv_score` or robustness
  - mark them as pending leaderboard validation
  - queue the strongest notebook for the next submission window

## How to Run
- `./autoresearch.sh --local-only`
- `./autoresearch.sh --submit`

## Files in Scope
- `notebook.py` — editable Kaggle notebook source of truth.
- `notebook.ipynb` — generated upload artifact.
- `build_notebook.py` — renders `notebook.py` into notebook JSON.
- `kernel-metadata.json` — Kaggle kernel packaging and resource flags.
- `__SUBMISSION_ARTIFACT__` — submission file produced by the local or Kaggle run.
- __FILES_IN_SCOPE__

## Off Limits
- __OFF_LIMITS__
- Any leaked labels or evaluation target leakage.
- Any dataset, model, or notebook disallowed by the competition rules.
- Private sharing or collaboration patterns the competition forbids.

## Constraints
- __CONSTRAINTS__
- Stay inside the written Kaggle rules at all times.
- Do not spend submissions carelessly; preserve quota for high-confidence candidates.
- Keep every scored notebook run inside the runtime budget with margin; if a candidate is too close to the cap, simplify it before submission.

